Absolutely — since you want to replace these explicit constructors with the builder pattern, here’s how you can rewrite your code using CompanyDTO.builder() instead of new CompanyDTO(...).

⸻

Assuming CompanyDTO has Lombok’s @Builder:

@Data
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
@Builder
public class CompanyDTO {
    private String identifier;
    private String legalName;
    private String intracommunityVATNumber;
    // other fields...
}


⸻

Original code:

new CompanyDTO(data.getRelationships().getPerson().getData().getId());

CompanyDTO companyDTO = new CompanyDTO("793115320", "OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A", "FR89793115320");
LegalEntity company = new LegalEntity();
CompanyDTO expectedCompany = new CompanyDTO("793115320", "OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A", "FR89793115320");
LegalEntity expectedLegalEntity = new LegalEntity("793115320", "OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A", "FR89793115320");


⸻

Rewritten with builder:

// Single identifier
CompanyDTO singleIdCompanyDTO = CompanyDTO.builder()
        .identifier(data.getRelationships().getPerson().getData().getId())
        .build();

// Full company info
CompanyDTO companyDTO = CompanyDTO.builder()
        .identifier("793115320")
        .legalName("OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A")
        .intracommunityVATNumber("FR89793115320")
        .build();

// Expected company for tests
CompanyDTO expectedCompany = CompanyDTO.builder()
        .identifier("793115320")
        .legalName("OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A")
        .intracommunityVATNumber("FR89793115320")
        .build();

// LegalEntity examples (if you also want builder for that)
LegalEntity expectedLegalEntity = LegalEntity.builder()
        .identifier("793115320")
        .legalName("OLKY PAYMENT SERVICE PROVIDER S.A")
        .intracommunityVATNumber("FR89793115320")
        .build();


⸻

✅ Benefits:
	1.	No more ambiguous constructors → MapStruct works without errors.
	2.	More readable for objects with multiple fields.
	3.	You can selectively set only the fields you need.

